{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/dry-eye-syndrome/background-information/prevalence/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"34c2a996-2361-578e-9016-983d6557b01f","slug":"prevalence","fullItemName":"Prevalence","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 76a8370e-f1c1-4e69-9547-9fa140ccddc9 --><h2>How common is it?</h2><!-- end field 76a8370e-f1c1-4e69-9547-9fa140ccddc9 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 7411e8a6-1465-446c-9e5f-d6463a220fd8 --><!-- begin field bfede2d7-4ae7-46dc-ac1f-4938127adef3 --><ul><li>Dry eye syndrome is estimated to affect between 5% and 33% of the adult population worldwide [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dry-eye-syndrome/references/\">DEWS, 2007</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dry-eye-syndrome/references/\">McDonald, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dry-eye-syndrome/references/\">Pucker, 2016</a>].<ul><li>Prevalence estimates vary depending on the definition of dry eye disease used, age of the cohort and country where the study was conducted [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dry-eye-syndrome/references/\">Prokopich, 2014</a>].</li><li>Dry eye syndrome is more common in people aged 50 years or older, in females and in those who have had refractive surgery [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dry-eye-syndrome/references/\">Schaumberg, 2003</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dry-eye-syndrome/references/\">DEWS, 2007</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dry-eye-syndrome/references/\">Lemp, 2008</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dry-eye-syndrome/references/\">Schaumberg, 2009</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dry-eye-syndrome/references/\">Pucker, 2016</a>].<ul><li>The prevalence of dry eye syndrome increases from 7.5% in people aged in their fifties to 15% in people aged in their seventies [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dry-eye-syndrome/references/\">College of Optometrists, 2015</a>].</li><li>The male to female ratio is 2:3 [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dry-eye-syndrome/references/\">Bron, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dry-eye-syndrome/references/\">College of Optometrists, 2015</a>].</li><li>One population-based cross-sectional study (n = 3,824 women aged 20–87 years) using data from the TwinsUK study found that 9.6% of women had a diagnosis of dry eye disease and 20.8% had had dry eye symptoms in the preceding 3 months. The highest effect sizes were found in women with depression, pelvic pain, irritable bowel syndrome or chronic widespread pain syndrome (p<0.0005) [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dry-eye-syndrome/references/\">Vehof, 2014</a>].</li></ul></li></ul></li><li>A US study using retrospective data from the National Veterans Administration (VA) database (n = 3.41 million visits to VA eye clinics [17.4% with dry eye disease]) suggested that prevalence of dry eye may vary with season.<ul><li>In the study, prevalence was found to be highest in winter and spring (18.7%±0.98 and 18.5%±4.16 respectively) and lowest in summer (15.3%±0.82) [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/dry-eye-syndrome/references/\">Kumar, 2015</a>].</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field bfede2d7-4ae7-46dc-ac1f-4938127adef3 --><!-- end item 7411e8a6-1465-446c-9e5f-d6463a220fd8 -->","topic":{"id":"386fd023-80c8-5773-9545-27347387cc3b","topicId":"19fd4567-edfc-4646-8106-bd391e9fc519","topicName":"Dry eye syndrome","slug":"dry-eye-syndrome","lastRevised":"Last revised in August 2017","chapters":